bios.P2721506: Robert Bright was the Bristol director of the GWR from the first full committee meeting in July 1833, and was one of the largest overall investors in the railway.  He was also a pricipal director of the Great Western Steam Ship company, in which he was a key figure, alongside Thomas Guppy.  He was the business partner of another major GWR investor, George Gibbs, in the company Gibbs, Bright & Co., which operated in the dry goods trade with the Caribbean and later extensively in cargo and passenger shipping to Australasia.  Along with Gibbs, he was also a recipient of compensation payments at the abolition of slavery.  His father was a Unitarian and leading Bristol Dissenter and his brother Richard was Brunel’s doctor, a leading nephrologist who was the first to describe what became known as Bright’s Disease, a kidney ailment linked to Brunel's death in 1859.
bios.Pd6a0186: Isambard Kingdom Brunel was hired, alongside W. H. Townsend, to survey the route of the Great Western Railway in 1833.  He was well-known to many Bristol figures through his design and plan for the Clifton Suspension Bridge, and surveying work on the city's floating harbour, conducted in 1832.  When the early committees of the GWR met,  Brunel featured in their correspondence and planning from the outset.   In 1835, when the building of the GWR gained Royal Assent, Brunel was immediately appointed chief engineer, and from that point on became the central figure in the designing, planning and building of the railway, down to the finest details of each bridge and station stop - including the original Bristol terminus, much of which still stands today as the Engine Shed.
bios.Pb20d45c: Henry Bush was a member of a prominent Bristol merchant family, and president of Bristol Chamber of Commerce during the 1830s.  Like many other indivudals associated with the early GWR, he was elected a Trustee of the Clifton Suspension Bridge in 1830 as part of the original committee that chose to build Brunel's design, and would later be a figure in the Great Western Steam Ship Company.
bios.Pa3ce1c5: John Cave was a prominent figure of Bristol's corportate and political structure on the eve of the GWR.  He was Sheriff of Bristol in 1822, Mayor of Bristol in 1828, Master of the Society of Merchant Venturers, and like many other early GWR members, a Trustee of the Clifton Suspension Bridge from 1830.  In early 1833 he joined Guppy, Harford, Jones and Tothill, along with other new members of the provisional committee, to form the embryonic board of the Great Western Railway, becoming a major investor.
bios.Pfed182f: Charles Bowles Fripp was a Liberal member of Bristol City Council in the 1830s, and appointed a Trustee for the Clifton Suspension Bridge in 1830.  He developed a close relationship with Brunel, who hired Fripp's son as an architectural assistant, whilst Fripp sr. went on to serve as auditor of the Great Western Steam Ship Company, as well as a director for Brunel's next major railway after the GWR, the Bristol & Exeter, whose original terminus stands opposite the Engine Shed today.
bios.P98a6076: George Gibbs was a business partner of Robert Bright in the Caribbean dry goods trade and later in Australasian trade and was, along with Bright, a recipient of compensation payments at the abolition of slavery.  He was an advocate of Brunel and his designs at the GWR board, which were often seen as expensive and elaborate, whilst his cousin, George H. Gibbs, proved a key advocate for Brunel at the London end of the GWR, where he was a central figure in fundraising for the London end of the line.
bios.P6287351: Thomas Guppy was one of the four original proponents of the GWR alongside William Tothill, George Jones, and John Harford.   From 1832, the group met at premises on Temple Back to discuss a major inter-city line between Bristol and London.  The same group had previosuly advocated, (and would construct) a 'Bristol & Gloucester Railway' which linked Coalpit Heath with the city harbour for the exclusive carriage of freight. Guppy, as with many other men on the GWR committee, was a founding member of the Bristol Chamber of Commerce in 1823, which sought ways - often technological - to boost the city's declining commerce.  Although he had apprenticed as an engineer, his own trade lay in sugar refining, conducted, with his brother, in both Bristol and New York.  He was a Trustee for Clifton Suspension Bridge from 1830, and appears to have first met Brunel in person during the Chartist Riots of 1832.  His relationship with Brunel was very close, with Guppy also serving as the major force behind the Great Western Steam Ship company, for which Brunel constructed the SS Great Britain.  Guppy became one of the largest shareholders in the GWR, and would later set up successful engineering works in Italy.
bios.Pdeb7853: John Harford was one of the original progenitors of the GWR, meeting with Thomas Guppy, William Tothill and George Jones in Temple Back in 1832.  He was from a prominent Bristol banking family, the Miles & Harford Bank, which served as the Bristol-based bank of the GWR, although he was not an active member of the business.  From 1830 he was a Trustee of Clifton Suspension Bridge, and from 1831 its Chairman, overseeing the decision to build Brunel's design. He was educated at Oxford, briefly an MP for Cardiganshire and a friend of William Wilberforce.  Unusually for many of Bristol's commercial elite involved in the Clifton Suspension Bridge and GWR, he was not a member of the Society of Merchant Venturers.
bios.Pdee2bf3: William Singer Jacque was President of Bristol Chamber of Commerce from 1832-34, and was invited to the first provisional committee to discuss the creation of the GWR.  He was elected as Liberal city councillor in 1836, and in 1839 extended his association with Brunel by becoming a Trustee of Clifton Suspension Bridge.
bios.P702529c: James Lean was Sheriff of Brisol in 1833 and an early investor and committee member for the GWR.
bios.P8a44cdd: Maze came from a merchant family and was a core member of Bristol's commercial community. He was vice president of Bristol Chamber of Commerce, director of Bristol Dock Company, and was invited to the provisional committe meeting of the GWR, for which he would later become a director.  Later still, he also became an investor in the Great Western Steam Ship Company and the Great Western Cotton Works, at Barton Hill.  Maze was an unsuccesful claimant for compensation after the British abolition of slavery.
bios.Pc4921eb: William Tothill was one of the four founding members of the GWR, alongside Thomas Guppy, John Haford and George Jones.  Like Guppy, his background was in industry, with Tothill operating as a manufacturing chemist.  Through his marriage to Hannah Darby, he was also a member of the Coalbrookdale industrial dynasty - which would later supply the iron used to build the SS Great Britain.
bios.P17d4b10: George H. Gibbs, of London, was the cousin of George Gibbs, of Bristol.  George H's father was Anthony Gibbs, whose company Anthony Gibbs & Sons were major global marine traders and insurers during the 19th century.  The family estate was developed at Tyntsfield.  George H was an enthusiasic fundraiser for (as well as investor in) the GWR in London, and developed a close relationsghip with both Brunel and the construction process of the line.

value.description: In 1832, the original projectors of what would eventually become the Great Wester Railway, Thomas Guppy, George Jones, William Tothill and John Harford first meet at premises on Temple Back.
In January 1833, a provisional committee of what would later become the GWR board meet for for the first time

In March 1833, a smaller sub-committee nominates Isambard Kingdom Brunel to survey a route for the Great Western Railway, based on the reccomendation of Nicholas Roch.  W H Townsend joins Brunel as a land surveyor.

In July 1833, the GWR formalises a board of directors, with one to serve Bristol, drawn largely from the original projectors, and one to serve London, bringing london interests into the railway.  Some original projectors drop away, whilst other key individuals of the railways future join.

On September 15, 1835, after gaining Royal Assent to construct a railway from Bristol to London, the GWR board nominate Brunel as Chief Engineer.  Thereafter, Brunel would become the principal driving force of the company

On October 1, 1835, shares in the GWR opens to investors.  The original Bristol projectors, and their relatives, contacts and business partners in Bath, Bristol and London are the largest subscribers in company stock.
In May 1836, a committee meeting of the GWR decides to purchase of the Temple Meads site as the terminus for the Bristol end of the railway.
In 1839, Brunel submits plans to the board for the design of the Bristol Terminus at Temple Meads, including passenger and locomotive facilities - the building that would become the 'Engine Shed'
In 1840, as the line nears completion at the Bristol end, Messrs Isaac and John Brown are awarded the contract to construct the Bristol terminus.
The GWR board holds its first meeting at the 'Offices, Terminus, Temple Meads, Bristol' on March 24, 1841

On June 30, 1841, the Great Western Railway opens, and the Bristol terminus receives its first passenegrs - among them Brunel and members of the board, who departed Paddington at 8am, and reached Bristol around midday.
